glosses: to sulk, to act cold and distant
to ensconce oneself due to the cold

etymology: Inherited from Old Anatolian Turkish دُمِشْمَقْ (/⁠dumışmaq⁠/). Tietze connects with domalmak (“to get on all fours”) comparing the third and fourth sense, and suggests an origin from Proto-Turkic *tom. However, this fails to account for the dialectal variations with a nasal /ŋ/ sound. Cognate with Chagatai توموشماق (twmwšmʾq, “to sulk”).
